    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-10-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-10-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="179"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d179">
                <head>179. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d179fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives and Records Administration, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1964–66, POL <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>.
                        Secret; <gloss target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>. Drafted and initialed by
                            <persName corresp="#p_TLE1">Thompson</persName> and approved in the
                        White House on October 13.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1966-10-10">October 10,
                            1966</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Soviet Greetings</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">U.S.</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>The President</item>
                            <item>The Secretary</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_TLE1">Llewellyn E. Thompson</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt Rostow</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR1">
                            <hi rend="italic">U.S.S.R.</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DAF1">Dobrynin</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName>Sukodrev</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>At the conclusion of the talk between the President and Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>, the latter said privately to the
                    President that he had brought greetings from President <persName
                        corresp="#p_PNV1">Podgorny</persName>, as well as Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName> and Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KAN1"
                        >Kosygin</persName> and their best wishes for the President personally, as
                    well as for the United States.</p>
                <p>The President replied that he was very appreciative of this message and hoped
                    that Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> would take his greetings
                    to the Soviet leaders. He said he would like to repeat the hope he had expressed
                    when he first took office that it would be possible for Soviet leaders to visit
                    this country or for him to visit the Soviet Union.</p>
                <p>At this point the leadership of the Congress entered the room and were presented
                    to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName>.</p>
            </div>
